  "school": "ICT",
  "asset": "ES (E-mini S&P 500 Futures, JUN 2023)",
  "timeframe": "1H",
  "market_context": "On the ES 1-hour chart around April 17-18, 2023, price was moving without a clearly defined consolidation range between roughly 4141 and 4186. The analyst needed a method to define the range when no obvious consolidation was visible before looking for a deviation-and-retest short setup.",
  "key_observation": "When no clear range is visible, wait for an aggressive displacement back into the prior price area; then look left from the displacement to identify which highs were swept and mark the highest body as the range boundary to define the deviation.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Observed that no obvious consolidation range was visible on the 1H ES chart, so deferred marking a range until displacement appeared.",
    "Step 2: Waited for an aggressive move up over the prior highs followed by an aggressive close back down (displacement back into the range).",
    "Step 3: Looked left from the displacement to identify which highs had been run by the move.",
    "Step 4: Marked out the highest body of the swept highs as the top boundary of the range (around 4186), defining the deviation zone above it (pink box).",
    "Step 5: With the deviation confirmed by an aggressive out / aggressive back-in close, anticipated a retest of that level for a short entry.",
    "Step 6: Projected the target to the opposite side of the range (around 4141, the prior low) as the draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 7: Let price play out — retest of the deviation level occurred and price then delivered lower toward the opposite side of the range."
  ],
  "outcome": "Setup played out as anticipated: price retested the marked deviation level and then traded lower toward the opposite side of the range (prior low around 4141).",
  "lessons": "If a consolidation range is not obvious, do not force one. Wait for an aggressive displacement back into prior price action, then use the swept highs' highest body as the range boundary to define the deviation and retest entry.",
